{"kind":"project","metadata":{"categoryPathComponent":"Todos","role":"project","category":"Todo backend","title":"Use PostgresNIO to store your Todos in a Postgres database"},"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/com.opticalaberration.hummingbird\/tutorials\/Hummingbird\/Todos-4-Postgres"},"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"major":0,"minor":3},"sections":[{"image":"hummingbird.png","kind":"hero","estimatedTimeInMinutes":15,"chapter":"Store Todos in a database","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Now we have a working API and a way to test it, lets look into storing our todos in a Postgres database with PostgresNIO.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"backgroundImage":"hummingbird.png","title":"Use PostgresNIO to store your Todos in a Postgres database"},{"kind":"tasks","tasks":[{"stepsSection":[{"type":"step","code":"todos-postgres-01.sh","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You’ll need to install postgres on your system if you don’t already have it. Detailed instructions on installing Postgres can be found "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/www.postgresql.org\/download\/","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}],"runtimePreview":null,"caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Once you have installed Postgres follow the instructions on screen to start your Postgres database service.","type":"text"}]}],"media":null},{"media":null,"caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Note the SQL commands all end in a semi-colon. The "},{"code":"\\c","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" command connects to a database and the ","type":"text"},{"code":"\\q","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" command quits ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"pqsl"},{"text":". You can find out more about ","type":"text"},{"code":"psql","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/www.postgresql.org\/docs\/current\/app-psql.html","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}],"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The Postgres install comes with ","type":"text"},{"code":"psql","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" the commandline interface to Postgres. We are going to use this to create a new database and a new role.","type":"text"}]}],"type":"step","code":"todos-postgres-02.sh","runtimePreview":null},{"code":"todos-postgres-03.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We return to our project…"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null,"runtimePreview":null},{"type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"And add PostgresNIO as a dependency","type":"text"}]}],"code":"todos-postgres-04.swift","media":null,"caption":[],"runtimePreview":null},{"type":"step","media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"code":"todos-postgres-05.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In Sources\/App\/Application+build.swift…","type":"text"}]}]},{"code":"todos-postgres-06.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"we add a new requirement ","type":"text"},{"code":"inMemoryTesting","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to "},{"code":"AppArguments","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":". This will decide whether we store Todos in memory or a Postgres database."}]}],"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"media":null},{"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We then need to add implementations of this requirement in Sources\/App\/App.swift"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null,"caption":[],"code":"todos-postgres-07.swift"},{"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"and Tests\/AppTests\/AppTests.swift","type":"text"}]}],"code":"todos-postgres-08.swift","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[]},{"type":"step","caption":[],"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We are going to use "},{"code":"PostgresClient","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" from PostgresNIO for our Postgres support. The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"inMemoryTesting"},{"type":"text","text":" flag is used to decide on whether we should set one up. Note the Postgres configuration details are the same as the Postgres role we set up earlier in psql."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null,"code":"todos-postgres-09.swift","runtimePreview":null},{"runtimePreview":null,"media":null,"code":"todos-postgres-10.swift","caption":[],"type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"PostgresClient","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" sets up background processes that requires lifecycle management. You can add a service to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Application"},{"type":"text","text":" to have its lifecycle managed as long as it conforms to "},{"code":"Service","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":". This is done by adding it to an internally held "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ServiceGroup"},{"type":"text","text":". More details on "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Service"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ServiceGroup"},{"type":"text","text":" can be found in the documentation for "},{"identifier":"https:\/\/swiftpackageindex.com\/swift-server\/swift-service-lifecycle\/main\/documentation\/servicelifecycle","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}]}],"contentSection":[{"mediaPosition":"trailing","kind":"contentAndMedia","media":"hummingbird.png","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Setup a Postgres database to use with the Todos application.","type":"text"}]}]}],"anchor":"Setup-your-Postgres-database","title":"Setup your Postgres database"},{"stepsSection":[{"caption":[],"runtimePreview":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We start our Postgres support by creating a type conforming to ","type":"text"},{"code":"TodoRepository","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" that uses "},{"code":"PostgresClient","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" from PostgresNIO. The functions are filled out with dummy code just now so the project will compile."}]}],"type":"step","media":null,"code":"todos-postgres-11.swift"},{"code":"todos-postgres-12.swift","type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If we are going to be saving our todos to a database we are going to need a table to store them in."}]}],"caption":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"I won’t go into any great detail about the SQL calls. That is not the purpose of this tutorial. We will cover how you construct, send calls and parse their results with "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresClient"},{"type":"text","text":" as we proceed through the tutorial."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Return to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"buildApplication(_:)"},{"type":"text","text":" in Application+build.swift…"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"caption":[],"media":null,"type":"step","code":"todos-postgres-10.swift","runtimePreview":null},{"runtimePreview":null,"type":"step","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Use the newly created ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"TodoPostgresRepository"},{"type":"text","text":" and once the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresClient"},{"text":" is running call ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"createTable"},{"text":".","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"caption":[],"media":null,"code":"todos-postgres-14.swift"},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Update "},{"code":"buildRouter(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to take the repository as an argument and pass it to the controller.","type":"text"}]}],"caption":[],"media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"type":"step","code":"todos-postgres-23.swift"},{"runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"type":"step","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Back to TodoPostgresRepository.swift to start implementing our repository methods.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null,"code":"todos-postgres-12.swift"},{"media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"code":"todos-postgres-15.swift","caption":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Wait a sec! If you look closer that query looks like it’s got SQL injection. That’s a classic security issue. Except this isn’t the case here. The object being constructed is not a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"String"},{"type":"text","text":" but a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresQuery"},{"type":"text","text":" which uses "},{"code":"StringInterpolation","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to create parameter bindings for all the interpolated variables."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To run a SQL query call ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresClient.query(_:logger:)"},{"type":"text","text":" with the query string and a Logger`."}]}],"type":"step"},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"get"},{"type":"text","text":" method demonstrates how you get data returned from a query. The query returns a sequence of rows. You extract the data from the row by decoding it as a tuple. In this case there should only be one row so we return immediately as soon as we have it."}]}],"code":"todos-postgres-16.swift","type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"media":null,"caption":[]},{"code":"todos-postgres-17.swift","type":"step","caption":[],"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"list"},{"type":"text","text":" is very similar to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"get"},{"text":". Except there is no ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"WHERE"},{"type":"text","text":" clause in the SQL and we return all of the rows returned from the query instead of just the first."}]}],"runtimePreview":null,"media":null},{"caption":[],"type":"step","media":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"patch"},{"text":" has a complication where we only want to include the non optional values in the ","type":"text"},{"code":"UPDATE","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" query otherwise we’ll be setting database columns to null. You could do this dynamically and build a ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"PostgresQuery.StringInterpolation"},{"text":" bit by bit but it is safer just to provide the full query strings for each situation.","type":"text"}]}],"runtimePreview":null,"code":"todos-postgres-18.swift"},{"type":"step","caption":[],"runtimePreview":null,"code":"todos-postgres-20.swift","media":null,"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"And finally the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"delete"},{"text":" and ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"deleteAll"},{"text":" functions. This completes the implementation of the Postgres todos repository.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"code":"todos-postgres-21.swift","runtimePreview":null,"media":null,"caption":[],"type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If you go to Tests\/AppTests\/AppTests.swift…"}]}]},{"type":"step","media":null,"code":"todos-postgres-22.swift","runtimePreview":null,"caption":[],"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can switch the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"inMemoryTesting"},{"text":" boolean to false to test your Postgres solution.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"That’s us done, we have a working and tested Todos application.","type":"text"}]}],"caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The code for this tutorial can be found in the ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/hummingbird-project\/hummingbird-examples\/tree\/main\/todos-postgres-tutorial","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}